Turn your chocolate bunnies into cocktail mugs for your drinks!
column180: Chocolate Bunnies make the cutest cocktail mugs! This is one of my favorite ways to serve up drinks each Easter/spring. I like to mix up the Easter Island cocktail for these (rum, lemongrass, makrut lime, creme da cacao, coconut), but any dessert cocktail or stirred drinks like an Old Fashioned would be great poured into one of these.
column184: Be sure the bunnies are marked as hollow
column187: Before adding your cocktail/drink, be sure there is not a hole or crack in the bunny before pouring your cocktail. Learn from my mistake 😬
column190: Use a serrated or sharp knife to cut off the ears. Dipping in hot water helps makes a clean cut
column193: Mix up your favorite cocktail and pour in, using a funnel for accuracy
column196: Garnish with edible flowers and mint or makrut lime leaves to replace the ears your cut off (sorry bunny)

FROZEN FLORAL ICE BUCKET DIY for chilling your favorite wine and bubbly.
column180: This idea comes from my book Celebrate Rosé ! Full instructions in the book.
column184: Ice bucket, medium pot, or small bucket
column187: Smaller circle container like a soup take out container - be sure that it fits into bucket and the wine your are serving fits inside it
column190: Flowers, greenery, dried flowers, citrus fruit, cranberries
column193: Weighted material- I used a rock but you can use a bag of dried beans or other freezable material
column229: 1. Take your smaller container and make sure the wine you are serving fits inside. Place the container in your ice bucket, pot or bucket.
column252: 2. Add the weighted material such as a large rock inside the container. Be sure the container is centered in the bucket.
column254: 3. Add water to fill most of the way up the side of the container.
column256: 4. Take your greenery, flowers and fruit and add them to the water in the bucket. I used left over Christmas garland greens (such as cypress), pink peppercorn, red berry branches, kumquat, & cranberries.
column258: 5. Freeze container for a few hours until frozen.
column260: 6. Run warm water over the outside of the ice bucket to loosen.
column262: 7. Serve on a tray or plate. Add white wine or bubbly to the ice bucket to keep chilled.

column375:
How To:
Make a Simple
Macramé Plant Hanger
column467:
SUPPLIES NEEDED
  • Ruler   • Scissors   • Pencil 

• Painter's Tape   • Wooden Ring    

• 6-foot lengths of 3mm cotton cord (8)

• 2-foot lengths of 3mm cotton cord (2)
column563:
STEP 1:
Slide the cords through
the wooden ring.
column732:
STEP 3: 
Split the cords into 4 sets of 4.

From the base of the wrapping knot, measure 8 inches down and
make a mark with a pencil.
column824:
STEP 4: 
Tie two square knots on
two sets of cords.
column907:
STEP 5: 
Repeat the process on the
remaining sets of cords.
column993:
STEP 6: 
Separate the four groups again.

From each of the two center groups, take the two cords that are
closest to each other.

Tie two square knots in this
set of four cords.
column1076:
STEP 7:
Repeat with the remaining cords,
tying two square knots in
each group of four cords.

Make sure the knots line up
 with each other.
column1162:
STEP 8: 
Finish with a wrapping knot, and then trim the cord ends to the desired length.
